Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: Existing research in aspect-based sentiment analysis (ABSA) has largely focused on improving neural architectures—particularly graph-based models—that leverage syntactic structures like dependency trees to better align aspects with their corresponding opinion words. While these methods enhance local context modeling, they remain confined within sentence-level processing and domain-specific boundaries, limiting their ability to generalize across domains or capture higher-order semantic relationships. Moreover, current knowledge graphs (KGs) used in sentiment analysis typically represent entities and relations in a flat, triple-based structure (subject-predicate-object), which is insufficient for encoding nuanced, context-sensitive sentiment bundles involving multiple interdependent aspects and opinions. Inspired by the limitations of dependency tree pruning and attention interference discussed in Papers 1–3, I propose shifting the paradigm from isolated sentence modeling to a unified, domain-agnostic knowledge representation framework. This framework treats aspect-opinion pairs not as discrete tuples but as dynamic *contextual sentiment bundles* encoded via hyperedges in a heterogeneous knowledge graph. Hyperedges allow multi-way relationships—capturing joint sentiment contexts among several aspects, opinions, and discourse markers—while ontological abstraction enables cross-domain generalization by mapping surface-level expressions to abstract sentiment-concept nodes (e.g., "taste_quality" instead of "flavor"). Unlike prior work that optimizes intra-sentence alignment, this idea focuses on building a reusable, transferable sentiment knowledge infrastructure. It differs fundamentally by emphasizing structural expressiveness over sequential modeling, enabling downstream ABSA systems to query pre-encoded contextual sentiment patterns rather than recompute them per instance. The integration of formal ontology principles ensures interpretability and scalability, addressing a critical gap in deployable AI systems requiring consistent sentiment reasoning across domains.

